steps.description:
Remove any rubber sealing from the inside of the cap and then wash each before you store it, using warm soapy water and a clean towel for drying. Find wax supplies. There are a few ways you can do this – gather as many old, broken crayons together to melt and use as the wax or you can go a step further, hit the craft store and purchase candle wax. Another option is to use old, melted-down candles you find around the house. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/58/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/58/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Pick up a package of pre-waxed wire wicks. Do not worry about the wick length, as you will trim it to desired size after the candle wax has been poured. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4d/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4d/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use only undamaged bottle caps. If the cap is dented or twisted, do not use it for this project, as the wax may spill from the sides. Place one pre-waxed wick in the middle of each bottle cap. Place the wick in the dead center of the bottle cap so that when you burn the candle, the wax melts away evenly. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a1/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a1/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Leave the long wick intact, as you will not know exactly how low you want to trim it until after the wax has been poured. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4f/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4f/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Whether you're using crayons or actual candle wax, melt the wax the same way. Place the candles or wax in a small pot. Remove all the paper from the crayons before melting the wax. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Fill a larger pot halfway to the top with water. Check that the smaller pot containing the crayons or wax can fit inside the larger pot (with room to spare). {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Bring the water to a rolling boil and then place the smaller pot with the wax inside the larger pot. Allow the wax to slowly melt until it is of a liquid consistency. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/52/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/52/Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Bottle-Cap-Candles-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
